IPickup interface
Item { get; set; } may allow pickups to change what item they hold after creation, which could be unintended. 
If pickups should always represent one fixed item, making this property get-only would be safer.

Pickup
The class is structured clearly, but it has some cleanup issues like the unused _pickups field and several unused using statements. 

PickupManager
PickupManager is simple and easy to follow, and its responsibilities are separated well from the Pickup class. 
One thing to consider is that AddPickup() triggers an event, but RemovePickup() does not, which makes the event behavior a little inconsistent.

IItem interface
The interface is straightforward, but Effect() is a fairly vague name and something like Use() or Apply() may communicate intent more clearly. 
Also, requiring every item to expose a Player property creates tighter coupling than necessary.

ItemEffects
Using public mutable fields makes accidental changes easier and hurts maintainability. 
This would be stronger as immutable properties or a readonly record struct, especially since it is meant to represent shared effect data.

ActiveItem
This class looks incomplete because Effects is never initialized, so Effect() and ClearEffect() likely do nothing right now. 
It also has settable Name and Description properties that are never assigned, which makes the item feel unfinished.

AdrenalineItem
This is one of the stronger classes here because the cooldown and buff timing logic is easy to read and self-contained. 
The only concern is that directly multiplying and dividing player stats can become fragile if multiple buffs stack or if the effect is applied more than once by mistake.

TeleportItem
TeleportItem is well organized and the “walk back” logic for invalid positions is a nice touch. One design issue is that teleport direction depends on velocity, 
so the player cannot blink while standing still even if they are facing a direction. It also does not account for exiting the walls of the game bounds.

NoneItem
This is a good use of the null-object pattern because it gives the system a safe fallback item with a no-op effect. 
It would still be better to initialize Name and Description to something like "None" so the item is clearer in debugging or UI contexts.

Overall
The overall design is solid and shows a good attempt at separating pickups, managers, and item behaviors into different classes. 
The main things to fix are the reversed collision logic in Pickup, the incomplete ActiveItem implementation, and general cleanup around unused code and tighter interface design.
